'''Charles William "Butch" Wensloff''' (February 3, 1915 <U+2013> February 18, 2001) was an American [[right-handed]] [[pitcher]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for three seasons in the [[American League]] with the [[New York Yankees]] and [[Cleveland Indians]]. In 41 career games, Wensloff pitched 276<U+2154> [[innings pitched|innings]] and posted a [[win (baseball)|win-loss record]] of 16<U+2013>13 and a 2.60 [[earned run average]] (ERA).

Wensloff began his career in the [[Arizona-Texas League]] before joining the New York Yankees farm system. He played on various minor league teams for the next six seasons and made his debut during the [[1943 New York Yankees season]]. He pitched in 29 games, and after the season ended, he served in the [[United States Army]] during [[World War II]]. Wensloff rejoined the Yankees in 1947, pitching in 11 regular season games and in the [[1947 World Series]]. After the season ended, he was sent to the Cleveland Indians, and pitched in one game for the team before retiring at the end of the season.

==Minor leagues==
Wensloff began his professional career in the [[Arizona-Texas League]], pitching for the [[Minor league_baseball#Class_B, C and D|Class-D]], [[El Paso Texans]], a team not affiliated with any major league squad, in 1937. The team included future Major League players [[Bill Bevens]] and [[Milo Candini]], and one former Major League player, [[Jimmy Zinn]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=17384 |title=1937 El Paso Texans |work=Baseball-Reference |publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Wensloff pitched 34 games that season, going 17<U+2013>10 with a 4.67 [[Earned run average|ERA]] in 233 [[innings pitched]]. At the end of the season, he was the third most successful pitcher in the league in terms of wins and pitched in the eighth highest number of [[inning (baseball)|innings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=pitch&id=10389&sort_by=IP |title=1937 Arizona-Texas League Pitching Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>

In 1938, Wensloff spent his first season in the New York Yankees minor league system, playing for the [[Minor league_baseball#Class_B, C and D|Class-C]] [[Joplin Miners]] of the [[Western Association]]. In an exhibition game with the Miners against the [[Baltimore Orioles|St. Louis Browns]], Wensloff allowed eight [[run (baseball)|runs]] and failed to pitch for a full inning as the Miners lost, 12&ndash;5.<ref>{{cite news|title=Greenberg Hits Three for Circuit, But Reds Conquer Tigers, 14-11|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=24|date=April 15, 1938}}</ref> In 28 games for the Miners in 1938, he won and lost 13 games each and finished the season with a 3.48 ERA.<ref name=brm>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=wenslo001cha|title=Butch Wensloff Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference |publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Wensloff continued his tenure with the Miners during the 1939 season. By the end of July, he had a win-loss record of 17&ndash;2.<ref>{{cite news|title=Western Association|work=[[The Sporting News]]|page=12|date=July 27, 1939}}</ref> In his final season at the Class-C level, Wensloff compiled a 26<U+2013>4 record in 31 games, pitching 249 innings.<ref name=brm/> At the end of the season, Wensloff had the most wins in the league along with Maury Newlin of the [[Topeka Owls]], and was also third in the league in innings pitched.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=pitch&id=14572|title=1939 Western Association Pitching Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>

In 1940, Wensloff was promoted to the [[Kansas City Blues (American Association)|Kansas City Blues]] of the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]], a higher level of the Yankees' farm system, where he played alongside [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Phil Rizzuto]], among others who later played in the majors. In his first game at the Double-A level, Wensloff allowed only two hits in a game against the [[Columbus Red Birds]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pitchers Show Dazzling Power|first=Bob|last=French|newspaper=[[Toledo Blade]]|date=April 20, 1940|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=esspAAAAIBAJ&sjid=i_4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6684,3440001&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Wensloff pitched in 35 games, 27 starts, going 13<U+2013>8 with a 3.19 ERA in 178 innings pitched.<ref name=brm/> The Blues went on to play in the American Association playoffs that season. In the second game of three against the [[Louisville Colonels (minor league baseball)|Louisville Colonels]], Wensloff [[shutout|shut them out]] as the Blues won the game, 1&ndash;0.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blues Shut Out Colonels, 1-0; Play-Off Tied|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=September 29, 1940|page=B2}}</ref> Wensloff spent his second season with the Blues in 1941, and went 15<U+2013>8 with a 3.93 ERA in 36 games, 22 of them starts.<ref name=brm/> He finished the season eighth in the American Association in wins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=pitch&id=10078|title=1941 American Association Pitching Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>

Wensloff played his third and final season with the Blues in 1942. That season, he was one of five pitchers named to the American Association All-Star Team, which Kansas City hosted.<ref>{{cite news|title=A.A. Twinkle Game Goes To Kansas City|work=The Sporting News|date=July 16, 1942|page=2}}</ref> Wensloff won his 19th game of the season on August 24, 1942, pitching the shortest game of the season, which only lasted one hour and 20 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KakWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5SIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3238,399779&hl=en|title=Kansas City Continues Climb Back to the Top|work=[[The Milwaukee Journal]]|date=August 25, 1942|page=7|accessdate=August 20, 2010}}</ref> Wensloff had a 21&ndash;10 record with a 2.47 ERA in 33 games, had the most wins in the league, and was sixth in ERA during that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=pitch&id=10079&sort_by=earned_run_avg|title=1942 American Association Pitching Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> On September 27, 1942, the New York Yankees purchased nine contracts from their minor league teams, including [[Herb Karpel]] and Wensloff's contracts from Kansas City, which placed them on the major league roster.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wensloff, Karpel Bought by Yanks|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal|date=September 27, 1942|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=se4ZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6SIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6553,4512281&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>

==New York Yankees==
{{quote box|width=32em|align=right|quote="Off to a poor start, Wensloff has come along in grand style. His present record is 10 wins and seven losses but included in his bag are five games in which he limited the opposition to five hits and five games in which he limited the enemy to six blows per game."|source= <U+2014> ''[[Beaver County Times]]:'' September 1, 1943<ref name="roy"/>}}

Upon signing a contract with the Yankees, Wensloff spent the 1943 season on the Yankees' major league roster. During spring training, Yankees manager [[Joe McCarthy (manager)|Joe McCarthy]] had heard impressive things about Wensloff, though he had not seen him pitch often.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yankees Try Hand At Another Sport; Athletes Enjoy Basketball Workout in Preparing for Baseball Campaign|first=James P.|last=Dawson|work=The New York Times|date=March 20, 1943|page=20}}</ref> Wensloff made his major league debut for the Yankees on May 2, 1943 against the [[Minnesota Twins|Washington Senators]].<ref name=br>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/w/wenslbu01.shtml|title=Butch Wensloff Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=August 21, 2010}}</ref> In his debut, the second game of a doubleheader, he allowed four earned runs and seven hits in eight innings as the Yankees lost, 4&ndash;1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rcMwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_GkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6334,1905488&hl=en|title=Nats Win, 4-1, After 11-3 Upset|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=May 3, 1943|page=21}}</ref> He won his first game in his next pitching appearance on May 7, 1943 against the [[Philadelphia Athletics]], allowing no [[base on balls|walks]] and six hits in a 6&ndash;2 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=6 Runs Scored in Rally|first=Paul|last=Lazarus|newspaper=Berkeley Daily Gazette|date=May 8, 1943|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HSMxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OOQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1225,2715636&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> By the end of June, he had six [[complete game]]s in his first six starts. However, he was not receiving the publicity other rookies were, such as pitcher [[Jesse Flores]], and had four wins and four losses despite how well he had been pitching.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=axgOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gX0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4331,6608668&hl=en|title=Yankees' Wensloff Hard Luck Pitcher of Year|first=Judson|last=Bailey|work=[[Evening Independent]]|date=June 26, 1943|page=9}}</ref>

During the second half of the season, Wensloff remained a major part of the starting rotation. His losses included a 1&ndash;0 defeat in which he only allowed one unearned run on a wild throw against the [[Baltimore Orioles|St. Louis Browns]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oMUcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=q1gEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6600,2344439&hl=en|title=Bucs Gain on Dodgers|work=[[The Deseret News]]|date=July 22, 1943|page=8}}</ref> During the season, Wensloff added a [[knuckleball]] to his selection of pitches, which he threw regularly during the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=au0oAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4NEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4549,5730855&hl=en|title=Trailing World Sport Events|work=[[The Southeast Missourian]]|date=August 2, 1943|page=5}}</ref> As the end of the season approached, Wensloff was being promoted as a rookie of the year candidate, due to being second on the team in strikeouts, as well as his 13 wins.<ref name="roy">{{cite news|title=Rookie Pitcher Wensloff is Yank's New Mound Star|first=Walter L.|last=Jones|work=[[Beaver County Times]]|date=September 1, 1943|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pKYiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T68FAAAAIBAJ&pg=977,3414334&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Wensloff finished the season with a 13<U+2013>11 record and a 2.54 ERA in 29 games, 27 of them starts.<ref name=br/> He did not pitch in the [[1943 World Series]], though he was on the roster.

==Military service==
At the conclusion of the 1943 season, Wensloff enlisted in the [[United States Army]] and served in [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballinwartime.com/those_who_served/those_who_served_atoz.htm|title=Those Who Served: All Major League Players, Umpires, Managers and Coaches who Served with the Armed Forces in WWII|publisher=Baseball in Wartime|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> When the Yankees were preparing for the start of the 1944 season, the team originally had no idea where Wensloff was, as they had not heard from him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uncle Sam Cuts Down Yanks to Size of Other A.L. Teams|work=The Sporting News|date=March 23, 1944|page=7}}</ref> He was inactive for the 1944 season. In 1945, Wensloff was traded from the Yankees to the [[San Diego Padres (PCL)|San Diego Padres]] of the [[Pacific Coast League]] for Johnny Kreevich, allowing him to simultaneously pitch professionally and continue serving in the war.<ref name="WWII">{{cite news|title=Kreevich is Optioned to Kansas City Blues|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|date=July 2, 1945 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5VYVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mOQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3593,576260&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> In 10 games for the Padres, he won three and lost four with a 3.82 ERA.<ref name=brm/> Afer the 1945 season and the war ended, Wensloff remained in military service, and as a result did not play in 1946.<ref>{{cite news|title=38 still in service|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal|date=April 13, 1946|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nx0aAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ECUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3302,5156720&hl=en|page=2}}</ref>

==Later career==
After his service, Wensloff returned to the New York Yankees for the 1947 season. He made his first appearance at the start of June and pitched despite having a sore arm throughout the season, pitching infrequently.<ref>{{cite news|first=Dan|last=Daniel|title=Yankees Dealt New Blow by Injury to DiMaggio|work=The Sporting News|date=August 13, 1947|page=8}}</ref> In 11 games with the Yankees, Wensloff compiled a record of 3<U+2013>1 with a 2.61 ERA and 18 strikeouts in 51<U+2154> innings pitched, and pitched two innings of one game in the [[1947 World Series]].<ref name=br/>

As the 1948 season began, Wensloff did not report to [[spring training]], and was holding out for a new contract; the only time he communicated with the club was to inquite about his [[World Series ring]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hallucinaations|first=Dan|last=Hall|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=March 28, 1948|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3BsLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DU8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6562,4578644&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> At the end of March, he was sold by the Yankees to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for a reported $30,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yankees Sell Wensloff to Phillie Club|newspaper=The Miami News|date=March 28, 1948|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CVMtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t9YFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2269,6323468&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> Wensloff refused to join the Phillies because he did not want to play in the [[National League]], and as a result he was sent back to the Yankees.<ref name=traded>{{cite news|title=Indians Purchase Charley Wensloff|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=April 13, 1948|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ieoKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DE8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4558,4058818&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> The Yankees were also in trade talks with the [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]], but Wensloff refused to play for them for the same reason. The Yankees continued to look for a trading partner, and eventually traded him to the Cleveland Indians for an undisclosed amount.<ref name=traded/> With the Indians, Wensloff pitched only one game, giving up two [[earned runs]] in 1<U+2154> innings pitched on May 4.<ref name=br/> He was placed on the [[disabled list]] on May 20, 1948 with continued arm soreness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sanders Shuffles Off to Buffalo|newspaper=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=May 20, 1948 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IXgbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JU0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3068,2017876&hl=en|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> This later proved to be a career-ending injury for Wensloff, as he retired at the end of the 1948 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cleveland Indians Reduce Farm Club System to Fifteen|work=[[Christian Science Monitor]]|date=October 21, 1948|page=16}}</ref> Upon ending his career, Wendloff retired to [[San Rafael, California]], and died on February 18, 2001.

